         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">6/8/91. ¶  ¶ In one of your valuable Bulletins, dear Prof. Hilgard, you speak of Medicago turbinata as a plant, which has proved valuable on pastures there. I have here for many years distributed the ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">91.08.06a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Eugene Hilgard</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Bancroft Library, University of California, Berkeley, California.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">6/8/91.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In one of your valuable Bulletins, dear Prof. Hilgard, you speak of <name key="Medicago%20turbinata">Medicago turbinata</name> as a plant, which has proved valuable on pastures there. I have here for many years distributed the seeds (fruits) of M. scutellata &amp; M. orbicularis, because both are always free of any spinules on their fruits, in which respect M. denticulata is here such a wool-deteriorating plant. Now I have added to these two harmless species for the pastures here M. tuberculata, the fruits of which are only asperous. But M. turbinata is apt to produce spinules, and even if seed was taken from the variety without spinules, the plant may not remain free of them in time. Perhaps you have really M. tuberculata. I should like to see some fruits of your plant. I found out, that it must be <name key="Quercus%20densiflora">Quercus densiflora</name> which furnishes the principal tan-bark in California Can you kindly contribute some brief notes for the new edition of the select plants,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>The next edition of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Select plants</seg> was B91.09.01, but as that was published by September 1891 (see <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Victorian naturalist</seg>, vol. 8 (1891), p. 85), M must have already been planning the subsequent edition, B95.08.04.</p>
               </note> as from your local experience there several additions must have suggested themselves, while you used that work.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I have several citations from your Bulletins for the new edition<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Hilgard was cited a number of times in B91.09.01 and slightly more frequently in B95.08.04; he had been cited only infrequently in the preceding edition, B88.12.01.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20denticulata">Medicago denticulata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20orbicularis">Medicago orbicularis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20scutellata">Medicago scutellata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20tuberculata">Medicago tuberculata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20turbinata">Medicago turbinata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Quercus%20densiflora">Quercus densiflora</name>
            </p>
